very large paintings.

00:04:38.720 --> 00:04:41.840
And he had a very
large studio, and he

00:04:41.840 --> 00:04:45.350
would paint these on the floor.

00:04:45.350 --> 00:04:50.720
So it was just very interesting
for me to work with a painting

00:04:50.720 --> 00:04:53.150
when I was growing
up and watching--

00:04:53.150 --> 00:04:56.310
I don't know if I exactly saw
this particular painting be

00:04:56.310 --> 00:04:59.220
painted, but he was doing
those kind of works.

00:04:59.220 --> 00:05:03.950
And also he could really paint
in large scale and small scale.

00:05:03.950 --> 00:05:06.890
And I think like
Christian too, he

00:05:06.890 --> 00:05:08.990
could paint really
large and really small,

00:05:08.990 --> 00:05:12.110
but it's not so easy to
do to go between scales.

00:05:12.110 --> 00:05:16.400
And so I wanted to challenge
myself and do something

00:05:16.400 --> 00:05:18.110
that was a large scale.

00:05:18.110 --> 00:05:21.950
And also this space
really provided

00:05:21.950 --> 00:05:24.840
for doing such a project.

00:05:24.840 --> 00:05:26.840
CHRISTIAN AWE: Here you
can see some other work.

00:05:26.840 --> 00:05:29.300
On the right side your
father's work from,

00:05:29.300 --> 00:05:30.680
what is that, the '60s or '70s?

00:05:30.680 --> 00:05:32.550
SHINGO FRANCIS: Oh no,
that's from the '80s.

00:05:32.550 --> 00:05:36.160
So that's like '82, '83.

00:05:36.160 --> 00:05:41.990
And so this is a very
overall painting of his,

00:05:41.990 --> 00:05:43.940
and then this middle
red one is mine.

00:05:43.940 --> 00:05:46.800
And I'll talk about
that series later.

00:05:46.800 --> 00:05:49.420
CHRISTIAN AWE: So we were asked
to do something site specific,

00:05:49.420 --> 00:05:55.100
and the first idea was that
I create a wall painting.

00:05:55.100 --> 00:05:57.380
And the museum
asked me to do so.

00:05:57.380 --> 00:05:59.240
I said, great, when can I come?

00:05:59.240 --> 00:06:02.090
And they said, well, three
days prior to the opening.

00:06:02.090 --> 00:06:04.070
I said, wow, I can't do that.

00:06:04.070 --> 00:06:05.390
I need much more time.

00:06:05.390 --> 00:06:06.920
They said, OK, then one week.

00:06:06.920 --> 00:06:08.700
I said, I can't do that.

00:06:08.700 --> 00:06:10.940
So I had to come
up with a concept,

00:06:10.940 --> 00:06:16.970
and basically I painted on
[INAUDIBLE] on pieces of paper

00:06:16.970 --> 00:06:24.440
that are like 10 meters long
and in total 12 meter wide,

00:06:24.440 --> 00:06:27.770
like kind of an abstract
waterfall because the Sezon

00:06:27.770 --> 00:06:32.660
Museum is based on the seasons,
the four seasons, and all

00:06:32.660 --> 00:06:33.900
about nature.

00:06:33.900 --> 00:06:44.530
So here you can see me working
at the museum installing it,

00:06:44.530 --> 00:06:46.060
bringing it all there.

00:06:46.060 --> 00:06:49.130
It's always a big challenge
to think of something

00:06:49.130 --> 00:06:51.170
and go to a foreign
country and think,

00:06:51.170 --> 00:06:52.520
is this going to work out?

00:06:52.520 --> 00:06:54.380
How does it going to work out?

00:06:54.380 --> 00:06:57.790
How can I actually do this?

00:06:57.790 --> 00:07:00.110
This is how it turned out.

00:07:00.110 --> 00:07:05.210
It was a pretty nice
process because the museum

00:07:05.210 --> 00:07:08.045
is one of the most
important ones in Japan

00:07:08.045 --> 00:07:13.710
and has this great collection
of artists like Rothko and--

00:07:13.710 --> 00:07:15.750
SHINGO FRANCIS:
Pollock and Kandinsky.

00:07:15.750 --> 00:07:17.000
CHRISTIAN AWE: --and everyone.

00:07:17.000 --> 00:07:18.725
And so everything is
very well preserved,

00:07:18.725 --> 00:07:20.600
and then comes this
young artist from Germany

00:07:20.600 --> 00:07:22.454
and starts ripping stuff apart.

00:07:22.454 --> 00:07:24.370
And they're like, oh my
god, what is he doing?

00:07:24.370 --> 00:07:26.480
Is he destroying things?

00:07:26.480 --> 00:07:29.870
So here you can see that
I actually really ripped

00:07:29.870 --> 00:07:33.980
things and then took some
stones from the water

00:07:33.980 --> 00:07:37.520
and put it underneath and
then made it in layers

00:07:37.520 --> 00:07:40.995
as if it would actually be
like an abstract waterfall.

00:07:40.995 --> 00:07:45.670
And the piece is called
"Seazon", like sea and zone.

00:07:45.670 --> 00:07:47.837
And it's a resemblance
of that nature.

00:07:47.837 --> 00:07:49.670
SHINGO FRANCIS: And
then nearby also there's

00:07:49.670 --> 00:07:56.000
a waterfall called [INAUDIBLE].

00:07:56.000 --> 00:07:58.160
It's a thousand
waterfalls or something.

00:07:58.160 --> 00:08:01.341
And you got a picture
of that and seeing

00:08:01.341 --> 00:08:02.840
that there was a
wonderful waterfall

00:08:02.840 --> 00:08:05.750
right near the museum,
and it's the same water

00:08:05.750 --> 00:08:08.060
that runs through
the museum grounds.

00:08:08.060 --> 00:08:10.790
CHRISTIAN AWE: Yeah,
it's always about where's

00:08:10.790 --> 00:08:11.967
inspiration coming from?

00:08:11.967 --> 00:08:13.550
And here you can see
a little bit what

00:08:13.550 --> 00:08:15.440
is actually in the collection.

00:08:15.440 --> 00:08:18.932
A Calder on the right,
Rothko in the middle, and--

00:08:18.932 --> 00:08:20.140
SHINGO FRANCIS: Jasper Jones.

00:08:20.140 --> 00:08:22.310
CHRISTIAN AWE:
--Jasper Jones, yeah.

00:08:22.310 --> 00:08:26.630
Great collection--
Pollock, Rothko.

00:08:26.630 --> 00:08:29.120
Definitely worth to check out.

00:08:29.120 --> 00:08:31.610
But my mission is
not only to paint.

00:08:31.610 --> 00:08:35.650
It's also to act in space.

00:08:35.650 --> 00:08:40.460
So this is a painting I made
in 2012 across from the Stasi

00:08:40.460 --> 00:08:43.940
headquarters, so the former
secret service of East Germany.

00:08:43.940 --> 00:08:47.210
And this painting is,
for me, about freedom.

00:08:47.210 --> 00:08:50.300
Blue is the color
of freedom and hope.

00:08:50.300 --> 00:08:55.490
And red in the
middle, yeah, energy.

00:08:55.490 --> 00:08:58.040
And it's actually
also on that street

00:08:58.040 --> 00:09:03.050
where, in 1945, the Russian
army drove into Berlin

00:09:03.050 --> 00:09:06.890
and fought Nazi Germany.

00:09:06.890 --> 00:09:09.590
And in that building still
a lot of the former workers

00:09:09.590 --> 00:09:14.690
for the East German secret
service still work there,

00:09:14.690 --> 00:09:17.570
and it was quite an
interesting project.

00:09:17.570 --> 00:09:19.420
And so I started.

00:09:19.420 --> 00:09:23.420
We had a lot of problem
of right-wing extremism

00:09:23.420 --> 00:09:27.710
after the fall of the Berlin
Wall in that area, as I said.

00:09:27.710 --> 00:09:31.580
I noticed that everyone who
got engaged in art and culture

00:09:31.580 --> 00:09:34.950
opened up their mind and
became a better human being.

00:09:34.950 --> 00:09:39.800
So I thought, well, how about
creating an outdoor museum

00:09:39.800 --> 00:09:42.560
and painting pictures
in my district

00:09:42.560 --> 00:09:45.260
and then all over the world
but actually also like

00:09:45.260 --> 00:09:48.720
engaging the public in it?

00:09:48.720 --> 00:09:50.465
So I did not only
paint these pictures.

00:09:53.630 --> 00:09:56.080
First of all, the process
is quite interesting.

00:09:56.080 --> 00:09:58.170
This one is 500 square meters.

00:09:58.170 --> 00:10:03.520
So it was like as big as a
tennis court, 33 meters high.

00:10:03.520 --> 00:10:06.900
And then you can
see with a sketch.

00:10:06.900 --> 00:10:09.970
So I was painting it
right on that wall,

00:10:09.970 --> 00:10:15.010
walking up and down 20 times
a day, 660 meters every day.

00:10:15.010 --> 00:10:17.800
So over a period of 12
weeks I climbed four times

00:10:17.800 --> 00:10:23.770
Mount Everest, which
in that process,

00:10:23.770 --> 00:10:27.190
forget about going to the
fitness center and the gym.

00:10:27.190 --> 00:10:29.120
Come and paint.

00:10:29.120 --> 00:10:32.980
I lost nine kilos
painting that painting.

00:10:32.980 --> 00:10:35.679
So here in that
black and white which

00:10:35.679 --> 00:10:37.220
just looks like an
abstract painting,

00:10:37.220 --> 00:10:41.110
if you look closely down
on that left bottom,

00:10:41.110 --> 00:10:44.185
that's me actually standing
in the scaffolding.

00:10:44.185 --> 00:10:46.360
Here you have that in color.

00:10:46.360 --> 00:10:51.734
They get like an image about
size, what that actually means.

00:10:51.734 --> 00:10:53.650
SHINGO FRANCIS: You
didn't use any projectors?

00:10:53.650 --> 00:10:55.483
CHRISTIAN AWE: No, I
didn't use a projector.

00:10:55.483 --> 00:10:59.230
First I though, how can
I actually draw this?

00:10:59.230 --> 00:11:04.322
So I just made it freehand,
but you completely lose--

00:11:04.322 --> 00:11:06.280
you have no idea where
in the painting you are,

00:11:06.280 --> 00:11:09.490
what is happening 5,
10, 20 meters above you.

00:11:09.490 --> 00:11:11.530
So I looked at art
history and checked

00:11:11.530 --> 00:11:14.180
out how did Michelangelo
paint the Sistine Chapel?

00:11:14.180 --> 00:11:16.730
And he was also there
painting it in Rome.

00:11:16.730 --> 00:11:19.100
And the first draft he
made was also wrong,

00:11:19.100 --> 00:11:21.100
and he had to demolish it.

00:11:21.100 --> 00:11:24.360
And he used a technique
where he first painted in

00:11:24.360 --> 00:11:29.220
on a piece of paper and
punched it with a nail

00:11:29.220 --> 00:11:34.840
the certain spots like where's
the head, where's the elbow,

00:11:34.840 --> 00:11:37.660
and then hold it up
against the ceiling

00:11:37.660 --> 00:11:43.300
and use little pigments to
powder through these holes.

00:11:43.300 --> 00:11:47.980
And when he took the
paper away, then a lot

00:11:47.980 --> 00:11:49.680
of transformation
points were there.

00:11:49.680 --> 00:11:52.480
So I did the same
process with a team,

00:11:52.480 --> 00:11:53.950
and we had the fun of counting.

00:11:53.950 --> 00:11:58.390
And it was 36,000
transformation points.

00:11:58.390 --> 00:12:00.010
So I love doing
these big projects,

00:12:00.010 --> 00:12:04.090
but what I love more is
engaging with the public.

00:12:04.090 --> 00:12:07.120
And over the 12 weeks I
had an open studio outside

00:12:07.120 --> 00:12:10.270
on the street, and I invited
the public every Friday

00:12:10.270 --> 00:12:12.550
for four hours to come
and paint with me.

00:12:12.550 --> 00:12:14.620
And I didn't know what
to expect back then,

00:12:14.620 --> 00:12:22.180
but over the 12 weeks I had over
1,200 people joining workshops.

00:12:22.180 --> 00:12:25.100
So there it was
clear for me, wow,

00:12:25.100 --> 00:12:28.090
there is a real demand for
people that want to create,

00:12:28.090 --> 00:12:30.500
that want to understand
what's going on.

00:12:30.500 --> 00:12:32.350
So that was kind
of a start for me

00:12:32.350 --> 00:12:35.410
to do this more professionally.

00:12:35.410 --> 00:12:38.371
So then I started working
with different artists

00:12:38.371 --> 00:12:39.370
from all over the world.

00:12:39.370 --> 00:12:43.420
Here, a group from
Singapore, Social Creatives,

00:12:43.420 --> 00:12:46.840
I invited painting
works together.

00:12:46.840 --> 00:12:49.320
And then I went elsewhere.

00:12:49.320 --> 00:12:54.520
Here did an artist in residence
in Princeton University

00:12:54.520 --> 00:12:57.970
and had the surrounding
suburbs that are actually

00:12:57.970 --> 00:12:59.260
pretty much run down.

00:12:59.260 --> 00:13:01.150
Princeton is very well off.

00:13:01.150 --> 00:13:02.350
The university is great.

00:13:02.350 --> 00:13:06.160
But what is happening around
it is like Trenton, Newark, New

00:13:06.160 --> 00:13:08.890
Jersey, kind of rough.

00:13:08.890 --> 00:13:11.020
So I organized the bus
shuttle and invited

00:13:11.020 --> 00:13:15.400
the kids who have never been
exposed to art and actually

00:13:15.400 --> 00:13:18.910
education much and created
a program for them to come,

00:13:18.910 --> 00:13:21.010
first, to paint on
shoes and T-shirts

00:13:21.010 --> 00:13:25.510
that they got for free
so they all would come.

00:13:25.510 --> 00:13:27.660
But then through that
you can teach them a lot.

00:13:27.660 --> 00:13:31.210
First you sneak in a little
bit Keith Haring and Basquiat

00:13:31.210 --> 00:13:33.640
and then taught them
some other stuff.

00:13:33.640 --> 00:13:36.640
And that developed into
a very great project

00:13:36.640 --> 00:13:41.880
where now this is still
ongoing and creating.

00:13:41.880 --> 00:13:43.090
Then I extended this.

00:13:43.090 --> 00:13:47.590
We have a big refugee crisis
in Europe, Africa, the Middle

00:13:47.590 --> 00:13:50.140
East, and started to
bring people together

00:13:50.140 --> 00:13:51.340
through art and culture.

00:13:51.340 --> 00:13:53.350
I say, let's paint together.

00:13:53.350 --> 00:13:55.790
There should be a
base of communication,

00:13:55.790 --> 00:13:59.800
and what could be better than
cooking, doing sports, doing

00:13:59.800 --> 00:14:01.240
music, or painting together?

00:14:01.240 --> 00:14:07.240
So this is a group of young
refugees with German students

00:14:07.240 --> 00:14:09.620
coming together.

00:14:09.620 --> 00:14:12.860
Here's some other
projects I picked.

00:14:12.860 --> 00:14:16.270
This is a series
of works in Germany

00:14:16.270 --> 00:14:18.950
at a cultural center in Berlin.

00:14:18.950 --> 00:14:19.670
That was new.

00:14:19.670 --> 00:14:21.626
Actually nobody did come
because nobody knew.

00:14:21.626 --> 00:14:23.500
The building kind of
looked like a little bit

00:14:23.500 --> 00:14:25.180
like a shopping center.

00:14:25.180 --> 00:14:27.790
And just after the paintings
were actually there,

00:14:27.790 --> 00:14:28.840
people started coming.

00:14:28.840 --> 00:14:31.930
And it's a very lovely
space also for music.

00:14:31.930 --> 00:14:33.610
That is in Russia.

00:14:33.610 --> 00:14:37.300
We created a project
in Perm, which

00:14:37.300 --> 00:14:41.680
is the most Eastern European
city in the Ural Mountains.

00:14:41.680 --> 00:14:49.120
And they're very well educated,
a lot of good-educated people.

00:14:49.120 --> 00:14:53.830
But they had a problem that
especially the young woman

00:14:53.830 --> 00:14:57.470
went away to Moscow, St.
Petersburg, or abroad.

00:14:57.470 --> 00:15:01.710
And the government didn't
know what was happening.

00:15:01.710 --> 00:15:05.240
So I had been engaged in a
lot of community projects,

00:15:05.240 --> 00:15:07.340
and they brought me in
and they said, well,

00:15:07.340 --> 00:15:10.224
you have to change something.

00:15:10.224 --> 00:15:11.890
You have to bring
culture into the city.

00:15:11.890 --> 00:15:17.720
It was an old weapon-industry
city, but culture was missing.

00:15:17.720 --> 00:15:20.720
So I said, let's
create outdoor murals

00:15:20.720 --> 00:15:23.180
of international artists,
of local artists,

00:15:23.180 --> 00:15:26.090
and let's change
the whole situation.

00:15:26.090 --> 00:15:32.750
And what happened was that
we created over 600 bus stops

00:15:32.750 --> 00:15:35.930
and really changed the
outlook of the city.

00:15:35.930 --> 00:15:37.730
And the background
you can see it's

00:15:37.730 --> 00:15:41.606
kind of just cold and
not really inviting.

00:15:41.606 --> 00:15:42.980
But then all of
a sudden the city

00:15:42.980 --> 00:15:49.010
changed and was a big cultural
approach, and a lot of people

00:15:49.010 --> 00:15:51.846
came in from all over.

00:15:51.846 --> 00:15:53.720
The best opera in the
world at the moment you

00:15:53.720 --> 00:15:54.710
can find in Perm.

00:15:54.710 --> 00:15:58.110
Even "The New York
Times" wrote about it.

00:15:58.110 --> 00:15:59.510
It's a big hub.

00:15:59.510 --> 00:16:02.180
And now they have a
festival called The White

00:16:02.180 --> 00:16:04.340
Knights of Perm, and
over a million people

00:16:04.340 --> 00:16:07.020
participate every summer.

00:16:07.020 --> 00:16:09.560
That's a project I
made in Miami where

00:16:09.560 --> 00:16:11.410
we changed the whole
neighborhood, Wynwood,

00:16:11.410 --> 00:16:16.010
that was really rundown,
really like a ghetto--

00:16:16.010 --> 00:16:18.740
just drugs, prostitution,
homelessness.

00:16:18.740 --> 00:16:21.080
Nobody at night
dared to go there.

00:16:21.080 --> 00:16:23.900
Even in the day it
was hard to go there.

00:16:23.900 --> 00:16:27.700
So with a collector friend
of mine, Tony Goldman,

00:16:27.700 --> 00:16:33.380
we changed the neighborhood and
brought art into the streets.

00:16:33.380 --> 00:16:37.460
And the concept was he was
owning a bunch of warehouses,

00:16:37.460 --> 00:16:39.860
and we created the
biggest outdoor museum.

00:16:39.860 --> 00:16:42.200
And right now there's,
I would say, probably

00:16:42.200 --> 00:16:50.120
over 400 paintings outside
for people to go somewhere.

00:16:50.120 --> 00:16:51.290
We created jobs.

00:16:51.290 --> 00:16:54.260
And there was a park, and in
the park a lot of paintings.

00:16:54.260 --> 00:16:56.810
And there's a
restaurant, actually

00:16:56.810 --> 00:16:59.240
one of the best
restaurants that I created,

00:16:59.240 --> 00:17:01.280
and Shepard Fairey made the bar.

00:17:01.280 --> 00:17:04.339
So people could come and
actually go, and a lot of jobs

00:17:04.339 --> 00:17:05.750
were created out of nowhere.

00:17:05.750 --> 00:17:08.810
You have now this cultural
hub, and that really

00:17:08.810 --> 00:17:13.408
changed the neighborhood
and created a lot of jobs.

00:17:13.408 --> 00:17:17.400
Here you have a project
just from the start,

00:17:17.400 --> 00:17:20.440
me painting a big piece.

00:17:20.440 --> 00:17:24.640
Actually somebody was owning
a big building in Berlin

00:17:24.640 --> 00:17:27.619
and he wanted to have
an outdoor mural.

00:17:27.619 --> 00:17:30.530
But he wanted to
sell the building,

00:17:30.530 --> 00:17:32.490
so he wanted to take the
piece along with him.

00:17:32.490 --> 00:17:35.300
And this is a little
bit the process.

00:17:35.300 --> 00:17:38.040
This is 12 by 30 meters.

00:17:38.040 --> 00:17:39.560
So I paint in different layers.

00:17:39.560 --> 00:17:44.030
That was over the
winter time, and then I

00:17:44.030 --> 00:17:46.820
had to install it
at the building.

00:17:46.820 --> 00:17:49.560
And this piece is
called [NON-ENGLISH]..

00:17:49.560 --> 00:17:51.950
And [NON-ENGLISH] means,
in different West African

00:17:51.950 --> 00:17:54.170
languages, a very warm welcome.

00:17:54.170 --> 00:17:57.710
I painted it 2014-15, just at
the beginning of the refugee

00:17:57.710 --> 00:18:00.930
crisis, and just
wanted to send out

00:18:00.930 --> 00:18:03.680
the message that,
yeah, people are

00:18:03.680 --> 00:18:06.350
welcome from the cultural side.

00:18:06.350 --> 00:18:11.060
And I used this
to create prints.

00:18:11.060 --> 00:18:14.570
And with these
prints I just started

00:18:14.570 --> 00:18:17.870
to build a school in West
Africa in Burkina Faso.

00:18:17.870 --> 00:18:23.850
And here's some images
from over there.

00:18:23.850 --> 00:18:26.880
The problem they had was that
the next school was over seven

00:18:26.880 --> 00:18:29.820
kilometers away, very hot.

00:18:29.820 --> 00:18:32.340
You have been feeling it
lately how hot it can get,

00:18:32.340 --> 00:18:36.640
but they are very often
around 40 and above.

00:18:36.640 --> 00:18:40.570
So walking seven kilometers
is just often not an option,

00:18:40.570 --> 00:18:44.800
especially as one of the
poorest countries in the world,

00:18:44.800 --> 00:18:49.110
they have a high child-mortality
rate, around 10% still,

00:18:49.110 --> 00:18:51.637
and a lot of young
women are not educated

00:18:51.637 --> 00:18:53.220
because they have
to go to the fields,

00:18:53.220 --> 00:18:54.720
help out with the family.

00:18:54.720 --> 00:18:56.650
So I said, let's
change something.

00:18:56.650 --> 00:18:59.340
And of the proceeds
of this painting,

00:18:59.340 --> 00:19:04.260
I started with a group
of friends and my partner

00:19:04.260 --> 00:19:06.570
to build a school.

00:19:06.570 --> 00:19:08.610
And the whole community helped.

00:19:08.610 --> 00:19:13.270
They were very anxious
to create something.

00:19:13.270 --> 00:19:21.270
And we did this, and the school
started in the last year.

00:19:21.270 --> 00:19:24.630
And it was planned
for 120 students,

00:19:24.630 --> 00:19:28.440
was so successful that we
now have over 300 students.

00:19:28.440 --> 00:19:31.650
And before they had about
a school rate of children

00:19:31.650 --> 00:19:33.750
around 40% to 60%.

00:19:33.750 --> 00:19:39.360
Now 98% go to the
school, and we are very

00:19:39.360 --> 00:19:44.040
looking forward to also
get to that 2% to go there.

00:19:44.040 --> 00:19:46.560
SHINGO FRANCIS: What was your
connection with Burkina Faso?

00:19:46.560 --> 00:19:49.950
How did you get connected
to this community?

00:19:49.950 --> 00:19:53.580
CHRISTIAN AWE: Well, let
