00:24:29.904 --> 00:24:32.320
SHINGO FRANCIS: My presentation
is more just about my work

00:24:32.320 --> 00:24:40.694
and about where I
draw my work from.

00:24:40.694 --> 00:24:42.360
This is a painting
that I've been doing,

00:24:42.360 --> 00:24:45.820
and it's a painting
that reflects.

00:24:45.820 --> 00:24:50.890
And what I've been
interested in lately is,

00:24:50.890 --> 00:24:53.590
well, in looking
at art and looking

00:24:53.590 --> 00:24:57.220
at images, a lot of times we're
really looking at our screens.

00:24:57.220 --> 00:25:04.030
And whether it's through
websites on our computers

00:25:04.030 --> 00:25:06.700
or looking at
Instagram, Facebook,

00:25:06.700 --> 00:25:12.880
what have you on our
mobile phones and iPads

00:25:12.880 --> 00:25:19.150
and what have you, at least in
the art world, a lot of times,

00:25:19.150 --> 00:25:21.430
and also people I
know, we're looking

00:25:21.430 --> 00:25:25.540
at images now distributed
through the screens

00:25:25.540 --> 00:25:29.370
and through digital
media and everything.

00:25:29.370 --> 00:25:31.090
And I find myself
and I find others

00:25:31.090 --> 00:25:35.320
talking about how we
look at art and that

00:25:35.320 --> 00:25:37.450
through looking at
art through the screen

00:25:37.450 --> 00:25:39.730
that we feel like
we saw the art.

00:25:39.730 --> 00:25:42.430
Like, oh, I saw this painting
or I saw this sculpture.

00:25:42.430 --> 00:25:46.000
And in a sense it's
replacing our experience

00:25:46.000 --> 00:25:48.070
with actually seeing
the real object

00:25:48.070 --> 00:25:53.990
because artworks are objects
that exist in space and time.

00:25:53.990 --> 00:25:55.840
And so I thought
about like, well,

00:25:55.840 --> 00:26:01.990
what would be a painting
that is either really

00:26:01.990 --> 00:26:04.690
difficult to photograph
or perhaps impossible

00:26:04.690 --> 00:26:06.430
to photograph?

00:26:06.430 --> 00:26:08.930
And of course you could
photograph anything,

00:26:08.930 --> 00:26:11.950
but I wanted to make
a painting that was

00:26:11.950 --> 00:26:14.030
really elusive in that sense.

00:26:14.030 --> 00:26:16.960
And so this painting
is painted purely

00:26:16.960 --> 00:26:23.770
with a type of paint that comes
from mimicking a beetle's skin.

00:26:23.770 --> 00:26:26.680
And in Japan it's
the type of beetle

00:26:26.680 --> 00:26:33.770
that they've been using to
make [JAPANESE] for kimonos

00:26:33.770 --> 00:26:35.150
for a long time.

00:26:35.150 --> 00:26:39.880
So from one direction
it's one color,

00:26:39.880 --> 00:26:42.400
and from another direction it
turns into a different color.

00:26:42.400 --> 00:26:45.640
So it's what they
call dichromatic.

00:26:45.640 --> 00:26:47.950
So they have these
dichromatic paints now,

00:26:47.950 --> 00:26:51.580
and I've been using them
for my own paintings.

00:26:51.580 --> 00:26:55.490
But since I started
thinking about how can I

00:26:55.490 --> 00:27:00.220
make an object that's really
elusive to photograph,

00:27:00.220 --> 00:27:04.280
I just started purely painting
with this pigment, this paint.

00:27:04.280 --> 00:27:08.130
And so this painting
on the top part here,

00:27:08.130 --> 00:27:13.450
it's kind of washed out, but
it's blue and it's green.

00:27:13.450 --> 00:27:16.000
So that's one color
when it's reflective.

00:27:16.000 --> 00:27:18.490
It's the primary color, what
I call the primary color.

00:27:18.490 --> 00:27:20.510
When it's reflecting
it's blue and green,

00:27:20.510 --> 00:27:22.120
and then when it's
not reflecting

00:27:22.120 --> 00:27:26.380
it's the contrast in
color which is yellow

00:27:26.380 --> 00:27:29.810
and like violet or magenta
or pink or what have you.

00:27:29.810 --> 00:27:31.690
So it's the opposite color.

00:27:31.690 --> 00:27:34.630
So basically these
colors just change

00:27:34.630 --> 00:27:39.040
depending on how the light
is reflected off the painting

00:27:39.040 --> 00:27:41.140
and how the light
sits on the painting.

00:27:41.140 --> 00:27:43.270
So you really
can't experience it

00:27:43.270 --> 00:27:48.070
just by taking a picture of
it because the picture is only

00:27:48.070 --> 00:27:53.670
going to reflect the way
the light was at that time.

00:27:53.670 --> 00:27:55.880
CHRISTIAN AWE: I think
it's quite beautiful

00:27:55.880 --> 00:27:59.620
that in this day and age
so many things are just--

00:28:02.980 --> 00:28:11.860
you can reproduce them, but a
lot of values are disappearing.

00:28:11.860 --> 00:28:13.300
Everything is mass produced.

00:28:13.300 --> 00:28:16.330
But I think art you
have to see in person,

00:28:16.330 --> 00:28:18.130
and it gives you something--

00:28:18.130 --> 00:28:22.005
it gives you an experience, and
your paintings of this series

00:28:22.005 --> 00:28:26.650
is definitely something that
has a certain aura you can just

00:28:26.650 --> 00:28:28.660
experience being there.

00:28:28.660 --> 00:28:34.450
And I think that is why art
will always stay valid and get

00:28:34.450 --> 00:28:36.315
even more and more important.

00:28:36.315 --> 00:28:37.690
SHINGO FRANCIS:
Yeah, and I think

00:28:37.690 --> 00:28:42.110
it's this thing about
virtual and real.

00:28:42.110 --> 00:28:44.050
Well, this kind
of painting forces

00:28:44.050 --> 00:28:53.040
you to see the object
in person, basically.

00:28:53.040 --> 00:28:57.100
So yeah, our experiences are
getting very much tangled up

00:28:57.100 --> 00:28:59.430
in-- and I kind of
brought this one first

00:28:59.430 --> 00:29:04.650
because this is a tech
company and a lot of things

00:29:04.650 --> 00:29:06.450
happen online.

00:29:06.450 --> 00:29:07.925
That is the platform.

00:29:11.130 --> 00:29:14.500
Yet at the same
time it's, I think,

00:29:14.500 --> 00:29:16.860
kind of negotiating
and navigating

00:29:16.860 --> 00:29:21.390
what we experience in
space and time as opposed

00:29:21.390 --> 00:29:28.950
to what we experience
online or what have you.

00:29:28.950 --> 00:29:32.610
And I think this is we're
in the new kind of era

00:29:32.610 --> 00:29:38.370
of whether-- even with
commerce and what have you.

00:29:38.370 --> 00:29:44.730
So just my background, I
grew up both here in Japan

00:29:44.730 --> 00:29:46.590
and also in the United States.

00:29:46.590 --> 00:29:48.750
And as a young child,
since my parents

00:29:48.750 --> 00:29:50.880
were separated when
I was really young,

00:29:50.880 --> 00:29:54.390
I spent my life in both places.

00:29:54.390 --> 00:30:01.350
And kind of like my segue
into art was really poetry.

00:30:01.350 --> 00:30:04.470
And specifically this
is William Blake,

00:30:04.470 --> 00:30:09.030
and he's an 18th-century
poet in England.

00:30:09.030 --> 00:30:13.410
And he combines
words and imagery.

00:30:13.410 --> 00:30:19.190
So he always has these
drawings that accompany--

00:30:19.190 --> 00:30:22.830
or they can be illustrations
that accompany his poems.

00:30:22.830 --> 00:30:32.710
And so I was as a young, I
don't know, teenager or so,

00:30:32.710 --> 00:30:35.590
I related to
reading these poems,

00:30:35.590 --> 00:30:38.530
and I could understand
what it's saying

00:30:38.530 --> 00:30:39.900
in relation to my own life.

00:30:39.900 --> 00:30:47.300
And that gave me the impetus
to say, oh, I can do this,

00:30:47.300 --> 00:30:51.740
or I can relate to this and
I want to tell my own story.

00:30:51.740 --> 00:30:54.070
So I started by writing poetry.

00:30:54.070 --> 00:30:57.860
And I was painting,
but it really

00:30:57.860 --> 00:31:01.030
wasn't something that I--

00:31:01.030 --> 00:31:03.820
it was more something since
my father was a painter,

00:31:03.820 --> 00:31:08.900
I got to get lessons
as a young child.

00:31:08.900 --> 00:31:11.500
And so that came in from
a different direction,

00:31:11.500 --> 00:31:14.590
but really where I really
kind of attached myself to

00:31:14.590 --> 00:31:16.720
at the beginning was poetry.

00:31:16.720 --> 00:31:21.370
And this is another example of
William Blake's illustrations

00:31:21.370 --> 00:31:29.170
or drawings where this is
the souls getting sucked up

00:31:29.170 --> 00:31:34.360
from hell, I think, and they're
going to purgatory or something

00:31:34.360 --> 00:31:35.150
like that.

00:31:35.150 --> 00:31:38.470
So he's kind of
biblical, but I thought

00:31:38.470 --> 00:31:40.300
they were really interesting.

00:31:40.300 --> 00:31:44.290
And I spent time in
Florence to learn

00:31:44.290 --> 00:31:48.280
how to paint in the more
traditional, classical way,

00:31:48.280 --> 00:31:55.870
and spent time there copying
various old master paintings.

00:31:58.720 --> 00:32:04.330
And then when I was in
Florence at the time--

00:32:04.330 --> 00:32:05.980
this is Joan Mitchell.

00:32:05.980 --> 00:32:09.910
So I was able to meet with--

00:32:09.910 --> 00:32:12.520
she was an abstract
expressionist painter as well,

00:32:12.520 --> 00:32:15.160
and she had a big
influence on me,

00:32:15.160 --> 00:32:19.210
something like what
Christian says about life.

00:32:19.210 --> 00:32:27.030
And I bring her up because she
was really emphatic in saying

00:32:27.030 --> 00:32:29.500
paint what you feel.

00:32:29.500 --> 00:32:35.890
Paint what it is that's inside
of you and bring it to life.

00:32:35.890 --> 00:32:40.240
And her paintings
are very expressive.

00:32:40.240 --> 00:32:46.810
They are emotional, I
think, very emotional.

00:32:46.810 --> 00:32:51.550
But I think it's a way to
express your emotional life.

00:32:51.550 --> 00:32:57.430
And I think there's also a real
freedom in painting this way

00:32:57.430 --> 00:33:01.540
and making your own marks
and your own gestures.

00:33:01.540 --> 00:33:03.160
This is my kind of
early work where

00:33:03.160 --> 00:33:13.140
I was painting these kind of
very semi gestural paintings.

00:33:13.140 --> 00:33:17.760
And then eventually I
started to kind of morph

00:33:17.760 --> 00:33:25.230
into different things, and I
got interested in coming back

00:33:25.230 --> 00:33:29.480
to Japan and Zen Buddhism.

00:33:29.480 --> 00:33:33.110
And that is something
I got interested in,

00:33:33.110 --> 00:33:35.530
like what is Japanese culture?

00:33:35.530 --> 00:33:43.020
What is kind of the soul
of Japan to say in a way?

00:33:43.020 --> 00:33:48.600
And Zen being something that
ultimately came from China,

00:33:48.600 --> 00:33:51.360
but in Japan it
kind of very much

00:33:51.360 --> 00:33:56.520
became a kind of
refined form of Buddhism

00:33:56.520 --> 00:33:59.560
that has a lot to
do about space.

00:33:59.560 --> 00:34:04.380
So I spent time at a
Buddhist monastery,

00:34:04.380 --> 00:34:10.275
and really it forced
me to kind of look

00:34:10.275 --> 00:34:14.024
into spending time
with your own self

00:34:14.024 --> 00:34:19.800
and sitting with your
emotions, your thoughts,

00:34:19.800 --> 00:34:23.540
and learning how to create
your own space within.

00:34:23.540 --> 00:34:24.590
That's pretty abstract.

00:34:24.590 --> 00:34:26.820
That's kind of an
abstract way of--

00:34:29.449 --> 00:34:33.230
it's hard to explain
in that sense.

00:34:33.230 --> 00:34:38.420
But I felt that, as far
as Japanese culture,

00:34:38.420 --> 00:34:40.340
that it's a big part
of Japanese culture

00:34:40.340 --> 00:34:46.060
is to understand
how space is used.

00:34:46.060 --> 00:34:48.909
And I think that's
really reflected

00:34:48.909 --> 00:34:53.620
for now in contemporary
architecture and design

00:34:53.620 --> 00:34:54.250
as well.

00:34:57.740 --> 00:35:03.840
And someone who kind of crossed
between the two cultures

00:35:03.840 --> 00:35:08.680
that I was really influenced
by as well was Isamu Noguchi?

00:35:08.680 --> 00:35:12.480
Anybody know of Isamu Noguchi?

00:35:12.480 --> 00:35:17.930
So he was someone that spent a
lot of time in both cultures,

00:35:17.930 --> 00:35:28.120
in the US and Japan, and learned
a very unique style of working

00:35:28.120 --> 00:35:32.440
with a Japanese tradition
and the European tradition.

00:35:32.440 --> 00:35:34.960
And this is his
place in Shikoku.

00:35:37.610 --> 00:35:39.620
It's right outside of Takamatsu.

00:35:39.620 --> 00:35:43.790
And he had a working studio.

00:35:43.790 --> 00:35:47.420
And so if you ever get
a chance to go there,

00:35:47.420 --> 00:35:51.770
I would recommend
going to this Noguchi

00:35:51.770 --> 00:35:53.600
Foundation in Takamatsu.

00:35:56.970 --> 00:35:59.370
And it's just his
way, his sensibility

00:35:59.370 --> 00:36:06.440
of bringing the Eastern and
Western aesthetics together.

00:36:06.440 --> 00:36:08.370
And then this is a
really interesting book,

00:36:08.370 --> 00:36:13.140
"In Praise of
Shadows", by Tanizaki,

00:36:13.140 --> 00:36:19.170
his philosophy about
space, light, shadow,

00:36:19.170 --> 00:36:25.380
and just kind of the simplicity
and the way light and shadow

00:36:25.380 --> 00:36:30.520
evokes emotions
and sets the scene.

00:36:30.520 --> 00:36:32.520
So I'm just kind of running
through these things

00:36:32.520 --> 00:36:33.936
since we don't
have too much time.

00:36:33.936 --> 00:36:41.190
And then on the other
hand this is James Turrell

00:36:41.190 --> 00:36:43.500
and one of his sky windows.

00:36:43.500 --> 00:36:48.010
So growing up also
in California,

00:36:48.010 --> 00:36:51.180
I was very attracted to the
space and light movement.

00:36:51.180 --> 00:36:55.770
And it's funny, he came to
Japan and got very influenced

00:36:55.770 --> 00:36:57.760
by Japan and brought
that back to California,

00:36:57.760 --> 00:36:59.470
and then he
influenced California.

00:36:59.470 --> 00:37:02.220
So there's this kind
of real dialogue

00:37:02.220 --> 00:37:06.690
going between Japan and the
West Coast of the United States.

00:37:09.320 --> 00:37:13.500
And this book, "The Art
of Light and Space",

00:37:13.500 --> 00:37:15.660
really explains the
whole philosophy

00:37:15.660 --> 00:37:18.150
behind the
light-and-space artists.

00:37:18.150 --> 00:37:20.430
And this is Robert Irwin.

00:37:20.430 --> 00:37:28.720
So it's this idea of
just taking perception

00:37:28.720 --> 00:37:33.790
and how our perception
is altered really

00:37:33.790 --> 00:37:37.750
affects the way we see
things and experience things.

00:37:40.770 --> 00:37:44.140
And this is an
artist Larry Bell.

00:37:44.140 --> 00:37:46.600
He made these glass
cubes, and they

00:37:46.600 --> 00:37:49.340
have a certain coating on it.

00:37:49.340 --> 00:37:55.510
And this also, it's
really another object

00:37:55.510 --> 00:37:59.100
you have to see in person where
it really changes depending

00:37:59.100 --> 00:38:01.590
on how you're looking at it.

00:38:01.590 --> 00:38:04.140
This is an early work of mine.

00:38:04.140 --> 00:38:09.570
So again, looking at
how perception works,

00:38:09.570 --> 00:38:12.610
there's a very faint
line at the bottom,

00:38:12.610 --> 00:38:15.630
and I think it's really hard
to see it with this screen.

00:38:15.630 --> 00:38:20.460
Right here there's like
a very, very vague,

00:38:20.460 --> 00:38:22.900
really hard-to-perceive line.

00:38:22.900 --> 00:38:26.730
One thing I think
is being confronted

00:38:26.730 --> 00:38:34.230
with basically a
nonrepresentational image

00:38:34.230 --> 00:38:38.030
of flatness or it
could be space,

00:38:38.030 --> 00:38:42.150
but you're confronted
with, in essence, nothing.

00:38:42.150 --> 00:38:49.590
And it's also in reference to
for a long time paintings been

00:38:49.590 --> 00:38:54.060
about making illusionistic space
like landscapes or the figure

00:38:54.060 --> 00:38:58.200
or what have you, and
then modernism really

00:38:58.200 --> 00:39:04.420
flattened out the plane,
meaning it brought everything

00:39:04.420 --> 00:39:07.030
to the front.

00:39:07.030 --> 00:39:10.690
So this has reference
to that, kind

00:39:10.690 --> 00:39:14.620
of really either flattening
out space or, in Japan,

00:39:14.620 --> 00:39:19.090
looking at [JAPANESE]
or [JAPANESE],, the void,

00:39:19.090 --> 00:39:22.570
and confronting the void.

00:39:22.570 --> 00:39:26.890
And that's kind of
a theme I've been

00:39:26.890 --> 00:39:33.050
very interested in with
my work, and I'm just

00:39:33.050 --> 00:39:37.700
really interested in
what people experience

00:39:37.700 --> 00:39:47.210
when they're confronted with
very little, essentially.

00:39:47.210 --> 00:39:53.480
So this is a show of what the
works look like an exhibition

00:39:53.480 --> 00:39:54.044
setting.

00:39:54.044 --> 00:39:55.460
CHRISTIAN AWE:
Which was also very

00:39:55.460 --> 00:39:59.990
nice to see at Sezon Museum
because we're actually

00:39:59.990 --> 00:40:01.390
quite contrary.

00:40:01.390 --> 00:40:07.700
You're like calm in
some of your works

00:40:07.700 --> 00:40:11.600
about emptiness,
nothingness, very reduced,

00:40:11.600 --> 00:40:14.300
and I'm more about energy.

00:40:14.300 --> 00:40:17.279
And your father actually kind
of hold us together and--

00:40:17.279 --> 00:40:19.570
SHINGO FRANCIS: Well yeah,
that's the interesting part.

00:40:19.570 --> 00:40:21.575
CHRISTIAN AWE: --built
a beautiful bridge.

00:40:21.575 --> 00:40:22.450
SHINGO FRANCIS: Yeah.

00:40:25.310 --> 00:40:28.970
My father uses a lot
of white in his work,

00:40:28.970 --> 00:40:31.700
but then there's a lot
of gestures and action

00:40:31.700 --> 00:40:35.120
going on between the lines.

00:40:35.120 --> 00:40:39.380
Whereas Christian is
very alive and colorful

00:40:39.380 --> 00:40:42.860
and a lot going on.

00:40:49.050 --> 00:40:55.130
So slowly these works
have certain compositions

00:40:55.130 --> 00:40:57.830
that come into them, but
essentially most of the work

00:40:57.830 --> 00:41:04.990
is you're looking at this very
either flat or deep space,

00:41:04.990 --> 00:41:06.850
depending on how you look at it.

00:41:10.030 --> 00:41:12.485
And these are some
prints I've been doing.

00:41:19.750 --> 00:41:23.360
And this is as you go along.

00:41:23.360 --> 00:41:26.460
And then there's some color
that starts to come in.

00:41:26.460 --> 00:41:29.850
So more recently
I've been doing ones

00:41:29.850 --> 00:41:34.740
where you're still getting
a majority of a very

00:41:34.740 --> 00:41:39.570
flat and static space with
some gestures happening

00:41:39.570 --> 00:41:41.620
at the top and the bottom.

00:41:41.620 --> 00:41:52.260
So that's really one of
my very interesting places

00:41:52.260 --> 00:41:55.330
where I'm really interested
in is what people experience.

00:41:55.330 --> 00:41:58.170
What is it when you're
confronted with basically

00:41:58.170 --> 00:42:02.580
nothing, but is it nothing?

00:42:02.580 --> 00:42:07.440
Is there something
to project onto it?

00:42:07.440 --> 00:42:09.510
How are you going
to respond to it?

00:42:09.510 --> 00:42:10.990
What is your response?

00:42:10.990 --> 00:42:16.500
And that is an inflation
shot of the works.

00:42:16.500 --> 00:42:18.240
And then there's
the body of work

00:42:18.240 --> 00:42:21.375
that has to do with this
band, like you saw earlier.

00:42:25.830 --> 00:42:28.710
So this is one of the
large installations

00:42:28.710 --> 00:42:31.250
like the one at Sezon.

00:42:31.250 --> 00:42:33.720
They could be enveloped.

00:42:33.720 --> 00:42:40.830
So these bands starting to be
about the band in the center

00:42:40.830 --> 00:42:46.260
being a certain space,
and then on the outside

00:42:46.260 --> 00:42:47.100
is another space.

00:42:47.100 --> 00:42:51.250
So for me it was more about
the internal and the external,

00:42:51.250 --> 00:42:57.810
so the inside being broken into
another space that has more

00:42:57.810 --> 00:43:01.680
to do with, on a
psychological level,

00:43:01.680 --> 00:43:05.310
on the internal life
of an individual,

00:43:05.310 --> 00:43:06.810
like what it is
that you're thinking

00:43:06.810 --> 00:43:10.680
and what you're feeling,
and then our environment.

00:43:10.680 --> 00:43:15.330
What is happening
outside of ourselves?

00:43:15.330 --> 00:43:18.130
What is going on in
our surroundings?

00:43:18.130 --> 00:43:21.330
What events are happening-- so
things that may be happening

00:43:21.330 --> 00:43:23.820
to us and how they affect us.

00:43:23.820 --> 00:43:28.240
And of course there's a
clear line between the two,

00:43:28.240 --> 00:43:31.560
yet at the same time
I think they very much

00:43:31.560 --> 00:43:32.790
affect each other.

00:43:32.790 --> 00:43:35.250
There's an affect that
happens between what

00:43:35.250 --> 00:43:37.590
it is that we're
thinking and feeling

00:43:37.590 --> 00:43:41.130
that gets projected outward and
then also things that happen

00:43:41.130 --> 00:43:45.000
outside of our lives around
us and our environment

00:43:45.000 --> 00:43:47.040
that affect our internal lives.

00:43:47.040 --> 00:43:53.457
So it's this play between the
internal and the external.

00:43:53.457 --> 00:43:54.540
I'll just keep it at that.

00:43:54.540 --> 00:43:58.736
[APPLAUSE]

00:43:58.736 --> 00:44:00.860
CHRISTIAN AWE: Are there
any comments or questions?

00:44:00.860 --> 00:44:01.710
AUDIENCE: Question?

00:44:01.710 --> 00:44:02.501
CHRISTIAN AWE: Yes?

00:44:02.501 --> 00:44:04.705
AUDIENCE: How do you know
your artwork is complete

00:44:04.705 --> 00:44:05.830
and stop painting?

00:44:05.830 --> 00:44:08.876
I am from engineering,
and as an engineer

00:44:08.876 --> 00:44:11.410
there is a concept
of overengineering.

00:44:11.410 --> 00:44:14.560
And we have priorities
and deadlines.

00:44:14.560 --> 00:44:19.130
All those force
me to stop working

00:44:19.130 --> 00:44:23.500
on some file or software,
to [INAUDIBLE] I mean.

00:44:23.500 --> 00:44:26.444
This is good enough, so
move on to the next one.

00:44:26.444 --> 00:44:29.170
How do artists
decide when to stop?

00:44:29.170 --> 00:44:31.160
CHRISTIAN AWE:
It's very difficult

00:44:31.160 --> 00:44:32.630
for different artists.

00:44:32.630 --> 00:44:34.700
Friends of mine
used to say whenever

00:44:34.700 --> 00:44:39.110
the transporter is coming,
the artwork is finished.

00:44:39.110 --> 00:44:41.450
For me personally,
it is a feeling.

00:44:41.450 --> 00:44:42.290
I know exactly.

00:44:42.290 --> 00:44:44.160
There are two approaches.

00:44:44.160 --> 00:44:49.100
One is that I completely just
create and experiment and just

00:44:49.100 --> 00:44:51.320
go with the flow,
and then I know

00:44:51.320 --> 00:44:53.840
how much I have to do until
something is finished.

00:44:53.840 --> 00:44:56.349
It just feels right.

00:44:56.349 --> 00:44:58.640
And when a painting is finished
for me, it is finished.

00:44:58.640 --> 00:45:01.112
But there are other artists
that always go back and say,

00:45:01.112 --> 00:45:02.070
I have to do something.

00:45:02.070 --> 00:45:03.080
I have to do something.

00:45:03.080 --> 00:45:06.020
There's a German
painter that is not

00:45:06.020 --> 00:45:08.480
allowed to visit
a lot of museums

00:45:08.480 --> 00:45:11.270
because his works are
in it and he can't stop.

00:45:11.270 --> 00:45:14.480
He goes to the works that
already belong to the museum

00:45:14.480 --> 00:45:15.724
and has his brushes there.

00:45:15.724 --> 00:45:16.640
SHINGO FRANCIS: Oh no.

00:45:16.640 --> 00:45:17.210
Oh my God.

00:45:17.210 --> 00:45:17.390
CHRISTIAN AWE: He
goes there and says,

00:45:17.390 --> 00:45:18.980
oh man, I have to
correct a little bit here

00:45:18.980 --> 00:45:19.938
and a little bit there.

00:45:19.938 --> 00:45:21.230
It's very hard sometimes.

00:45:25.340 --> 00:45:30.800
SHINGO FRANCIS: Well, I've
learned to stop before--

00:45:30.800 --> 00:45:35.330
it's easy for me to overpaint
something, to overly do it.

00:45:35.330 --> 00:45:40.070
And with painting it's kind
of hard because once you go,

00:45:40.070 --> 00:45:42.230
you can't really
take it off, right?

00:45:42.230 --> 00:45:45.710
And you can maybe go over
it with white or whatever

00:45:45.710 --> 00:45:46.210
and try to--

00:45:46.210 --> 00:45:48.085
CHRISTIAN AWE: It would
be great to have like

00:45:48.085 --> 00:45:49.530
a Photoshop go back button.

00:45:49.530 --> 00:45:52.570
SHINGO FRANCIS: Yeah, you could
go back in time or something.

00:45:52.570 --> 00:45:56.930
So I've learned over the
years that although maybe I

00:45:56.930 --> 00:45:58.460
should keep going,
but I say, well,

00:45:58.460 --> 00:46:01.410
I'll wait and wait until
tomorrow and look at it again.

00:46:01.410 --> 00:46:05.570
So it's kind of like
refreshing yourself

00:46:05.570 --> 00:46:07.580
because it's easy to overdo it.

00:46:07.580 --> 00:46:08.670
That's my experience.

00:46:08.670 --> 00:46:13.670
It's easy to say, oh man, I
liked it when it wasn't so--

00:46:13.670 --> 00:46:15.320
because my work,
as you could see,

00:46:15.320 --> 00:46:20.210
it's kind of like a
less-is-more kind of thing.

00:46:20.210 --> 00:46:21.350
And then you have a sense.

00:46:21.350 --> 00:46:23.810
It's like, OK.

00:46:23.810 --> 00:46:25.720
Same with Christian.

00:46:25.720 --> 00:46:31.310
It's more of a kind of a feeling
that if I do too much of it,

00:46:31.310 --> 00:46:36.130
it's going to just
lose what it has now.

00:46:36.130 --> 00:46:37.880
CHRISTIAN AWE: There
was another question?

00:46:37.880 --> 00:46:38.463
AUDIENCE: Yes.

