that since before or all of
a sudden you kind of decided?

00:47:10.710 --> 00:47:12.442
You were like, oh,
I want to do that?

00:47:12.442 --> 00:47:13.390
That's [INAUDIBLE].

00:47:13.390 --> 00:47:15.390
SHINGO FRANCIS: So
for the painting

00:47:15.390 --> 00:47:17.100
I did in response
to my father, that

00:47:17.100 --> 00:47:20.070
was a concept that
came from the museum.

00:47:20.070 --> 00:47:24.590
They asked us to choose a
painting from the collection.

00:47:24.590 --> 00:47:28.860
And as being a son of-- when
you're in the same line of work

00:47:28.860 --> 00:47:34.020
as one of your parents,
it's like you go through--

00:47:34.020 --> 00:47:36.750
and so in my 20s I really
went through this whole thing

00:47:36.750 --> 00:47:39.390
like, oh God, I have to deal--

00:47:39.390 --> 00:47:41.340
people always comparing
you and this and that.

00:47:41.340 --> 00:47:43.350
It used to bother me a lot.

00:47:43.350 --> 00:47:45.075
I thought about
changing my last name.

00:47:47.730 --> 00:47:52.260
I went through this mini crisis,
like oh my God, am I ever

00:47:52.260 --> 00:47:53.580
going to--

00:47:53.580 --> 00:47:57.150
it's this whole
Oedipus kind of thing.

00:47:57.150 --> 00:47:58.890
Do I have to kill my
father or something?

00:47:58.890 --> 00:48:01.290
Do I have to become more
famous than him or something?

00:48:01.290 --> 00:48:02.623
You go through this whole thing.

00:48:02.623 --> 00:48:07.950
And so I've had an
experience where

00:48:07.950 --> 00:48:13.900
I've kind of gone beyond
that and found how I work

00:48:13.900 --> 00:48:17.460
and what kind of
approach I have.

00:48:17.460 --> 00:48:22.320
So when I got that
recommendation it was like,

00:48:22.320 --> 00:48:24.690
oh yeah, I know
what I want to do.

00:48:24.690 --> 00:48:30.505
So it was pretty natural,
whereas 15 years ago I

00:48:30.505 --> 00:48:32.130
think I would have
had a total identity

00:48:32.130 --> 00:48:36.260
crisis, like oh my God.

00:48:36.260 --> 00:48:41.970
It would have been either
a competition in my mind

00:48:41.970 --> 00:48:46.050
or I would have probably
refused, would have been

00:48:46.050 --> 00:48:48.690
one or the other.

00:48:48.690 --> 00:48:51.540
So it was a good
experience this time.

00:48:51.540 --> 00:48:53.960
CHRISTIAN AWE: For your question
about community project,

00:48:53.960 --> 00:48:56.880
committee art, for
me being raised

00:48:56.880 --> 00:49:01.080
in East Germany in a
socialistic system,

00:49:01.080 --> 00:49:05.820
it was always very normal for
me to engage to do something

00:49:05.820 --> 00:49:07.370
with others, for others.

00:49:07.370 --> 00:49:13.350
It was never really
only for my own pleasure

00:49:13.350 --> 00:49:15.810
or for my own gain or wealth.

00:49:15.810 --> 00:49:20.310
So it was very normal, and
I feel especially whoever

00:49:20.310 --> 00:49:22.410
can should give something back.

00:49:22.410 --> 00:49:28.050
And as an artist, we have
a voice, so why not use it?

00:49:28.050 --> 00:49:36.800
And just treat people as
you want to be treated.

00:49:36.800 --> 00:49:38.580
Do something.

00:49:38.580 --> 00:49:40.230
Stand for something.

00:49:40.230 --> 00:49:44.130
And I feel it's very
interesting also

00:49:44.130 --> 00:49:48.870
how I feel that, for
example, Japan is opening up.

00:49:48.870 --> 00:49:51.870
Also with the
Olympics coming 2020,

00:49:51.870 --> 00:49:54.330
how you portrayed
yourself at the soccer

00:49:54.330 --> 00:49:56.940
championship cleaning up
the stadium afterwards,

00:49:56.940 --> 00:49:58.740
leaving nice notes.

00:49:58.740 --> 00:50:02.230
This is something,
leading by example--

00:50:02.230 --> 00:50:06.000
such a high-technology world
over here but then still

00:50:06.000 --> 00:50:11.400
so Zen Buddhism and all
about nature and giving back.

00:50:11.400 --> 00:50:14.400
And in a way, I think
leading by example

00:50:14.400 --> 00:50:20.009
and inspiring others
is what we have to do.

00:50:20.009 --> 00:50:22.050
And I actually really
liked how you said Awe-san.

00:50:22.050 --> 00:50:23.520
It was the first
time I heard that.

00:50:23.520 --> 00:50:25.080
SHINGO FRANCIS: Awe-san.

00:50:25.080 --> 00:50:26.726
We have to call you that now.

00:50:26.726 --> 00:50:28.025
AUDIENCE: I have a question.

00:50:28.025 --> 00:50:29.775
And thank you so
much for sharing.

00:50:29.775 --> 00:50:31.980
It was truly, truly inspiring.

00:50:31.980 --> 00:50:35.260
And my question is,
especially in Japan,

00:50:35.260 --> 00:50:39.880
we see different
forms and frameworks

00:50:39.880 --> 00:50:43.260
of presenting and
sharing art emerging.

00:50:43.260 --> 00:50:46.361
For example, now there
is an ongoing digital art

00:50:46.361 --> 00:50:49.980
exhibition by teamLab,
or you go to Naoshima

00:50:49.980 --> 00:50:53.450
and you experience art
pieces, installations

00:50:53.450 --> 00:50:57.400
amidst the nature that let
them shine in a new light.

00:50:57.400 --> 00:50:59.970
So I was wondering
in your perception,

00:50:59.970 --> 00:51:03.250
what is the next
phase in of actually

00:51:03.250 --> 00:51:04.730
sharing the art with others?

00:51:04.730 --> 00:51:08.160
What's coming?

00:51:08.160 --> 00:51:10.620
CHRISTIAN AWE: I think it's
very important to break down

00:51:10.620 --> 00:51:12.210
the barriers of art.

00:51:12.210 --> 00:51:16.020
A lot of people would never
go to a museum or a gallery

00:51:16.020 --> 00:51:20.800
or ask about buying
something if they feel

00:51:20.800 --> 00:51:24.690
forced to engage in something.

00:51:24.690 --> 00:51:28.170
I think it should be
much more normal to be

00:51:28.170 --> 00:51:29.460
taught at in school.

00:51:29.460 --> 00:51:32.230
That doesn't happen
everywhere in the world.

00:51:32.230 --> 00:51:35.700
It's all about mathematics,
physics, and so on,

00:51:35.700 --> 00:51:40.500
but I actually feel
that these soft values,

00:51:40.500 --> 00:51:46.680
you can learn best in writing
poems, engaging in sport,

00:51:46.680 --> 00:51:48.810
in music.

00:51:48.810 --> 00:51:51.930
What can we do in the
digitalized worlds

00:51:51.930 --> 00:51:59.150
where very soon machines can
do much more things better

00:51:59.150 --> 00:52:01.990
at a much faster space?

00:52:01.990 --> 00:52:06.450
What is the value of us humans?

00:52:06.450 --> 00:52:07.950
That is what we
have to filter out

00:52:07.950 --> 00:52:10.170
and that is what
we have to learn

00:52:10.170 --> 00:52:12.060
and being taught in school.

00:52:12.060 --> 00:52:14.835
And that is really the priority.

00:52:17.559 --> 00:52:18.850
SHINGO FRANCIS: What can I add?

00:52:18.850 --> 00:52:23.820
Well, these different platforms
like teamLab doing their thing,

00:52:23.820 --> 00:52:29.340
I mean, I think it's great
to have various ways to reach

00:52:29.340 --> 00:52:33.650
people, various mediums to
reach people to experience art.

00:52:33.650 --> 00:52:37.440
And teamLab making their
work that's catered

00:52:37.440 --> 00:52:39.330
to that platform.

00:52:39.330 --> 00:52:44.250
And there's a lot
of art now being

00:52:44.250 --> 00:52:49.580
generated through digital
mediums and what have you.

00:52:49.580 --> 00:52:55.890
And I mean film when it first
came into being, moving images

00:52:55.890 --> 00:52:58.410
with a completely new art form.

00:52:58.410 --> 00:53:00.750
And I think there's
always going to be

00:53:00.750 --> 00:53:10.490
new art forms being created,
and it's how you experience it.

00:53:10.490 --> 00:53:12.690
But I think it's important.

00:53:12.690 --> 00:53:17.460
There's barriers, this idea
about like art being exclusive

00:53:17.460 --> 00:53:24.720
or art being for, oh, I have
to have an understanding of it,

00:53:24.720 --> 00:53:26.975
that these notions kind
of get broken down.

00:53:31.180 --> 00:53:34.490
And the definition of art
gets kind of tricky too.

00:53:34.490 --> 00:53:37.680
Well, what is art
and what is not art?

00:53:37.680 --> 00:53:43.470
But having the ability to
have access for museums--

00:53:43.470 --> 00:53:46.710
well, the institutions
really need to step up,

00:53:46.710 --> 00:53:52.950
and some have-- step
up and make it more

00:53:52.950 --> 00:53:56.340
inviting so people
can understand

00:53:56.340 --> 00:53:59.340
what it is that they're looking
at, what they're experiencing.

00:53:59.340 --> 00:54:01.890
So text is important
in that part.

00:54:01.890 --> 00:54:07.440
And in education, it's
true, art gets cut.

00:54:07.440 --> 00:54:11.454
It's the first funding that gets
cut, and usually in education.

00:54:11.454 --> 00:54:13.620
CHRISTIAN AWE: Since we are
running out of time now,

00:54:13.620 --> 00:54:15.540
let me maybe end up with this.

00:54:15.540 --> 00:54:20.760
I believe that art is one of
the most important profession

00:54:20.760 --> 00:54:25.680
in a society, whether
it's free or dictatorian.

00:54:25.680 --> 00:54:29.580
I feel like that every
big company and even

00:54:29.580 --> 00:54:36.030
the politicians should have art
advisors and philosophers being

00:54:36.030 --> 00:54:42.480
to re-evaluate what the culture
is-- where are we heading--

00:54:42.480 --> 00:54:46.290
because artists are
among the most free,

00:54:46.290 --> 00:54:51.649
and we are not
really like bound.

00:54:51.649 --> 00:54:53.190
We don't have to
think a certain way.

00:54:53.190 --> 00:54:57.210
We are free thinkers and
therefore leading a way

00:54:57.210 --> 00:54:58.510
into the future.

00:54:58.510 --> 00:54:59.970
And that's why I
can just encourage

00:54:59.970 --> 00:55:05.020
companies and politicians to
have advisors in that way,

00:55:05.020 --> 00:55:06.687
into a better future.

00:55:06.687 --> 00:55:08.520
SHINGO FRANCIS: Well,
and the Greeks, right?

00:55:08.520 --> 00:55:14.300
Poets and philosophers
were advising the council.

00:55:14.300 --> 00:55:15.800
Well, thank you Eri.

